The Destruction of Sacred Objects in Colonial North America -- tFinal Reflections: Spenser and the End of the British Empire -- tNotes -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aReligion and empire were inseparable forces in the early modern Atlantic world. Religious passions and conflicts drove much of the expansionist energy of post-Reformation Europe, providing both a rationale and a practical mode of organizing the dispersal and resettlement of hundreds of thousands of people from the Old World to the New World. Exhortations to conquer new peoples were the lingua franca of Western imperialism, and men like the mystically inclined Christopher Columbus were genuinely inspired to risk their lives and their fortunes to bring the gospel to the Americas. And in the thousands of religious refugees seeking asylum from the vicious wars of religion that tore the continent apart in the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries, these visionary explorers found a ready pool of migrants—English Puritans and Quakers, French Huguenots, German Moravians, Scots-Irish Presbyterians—equally willing to risk life and limb for a chance to worship God in their own way.Focusing on the formative period of European exploration, settlement, and conquest in the Americas, from roughly 1500 to 1760, Empires of God brings together historians and literary scholars of the English, French, and Spanish Americas around a common set of questions: How did religious communities and beliefs create empires, and how did imperial structures transform New World religions? How did Europeans and Native Americans make sense of each other's spiritual systems, and what acts of linguistic and cultural transition did this entail? What was the role of violence in New World religious encounters? Together, the essays collected here demonstrate the power of religious ideas and narratives to create kingdoms both imagined and real.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 4aReligious Studies. 7aHISTORY / United States / Colonial Period (1600-1775).2bisacsh  aAmerican History.  aAmerican Studies.  aReligion.  aReligious Studies.1 aAdorno, Rolena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBross, Kristina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConover, Cornelius, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeslandres, Dominique, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErben, Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFuchs, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreer, Allan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGregerson, Linda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGregerson, Linda, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aIbbett, Katherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJuster, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJuster, Susan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPestana, Carla Gardina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStevens, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWiggin, Bethany, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package American Historyz978311041349608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311045954840uhttps: